Scalability
    - Ability of a system to handle increasing users, requests, or data without major performance loss.

1. Types of Scalability

    > Vertical Scaling (Scale Up)
        - Increase resources of same server
        - More CPU, RAM, SSD
        - Example:
            4 Cores → 8 Cores
            16 GB RAM → 32 GB RAM

    > Horizontal Scaling (Scale Out)
        - Add more servers/machines
        - Load balancer distributes traffic
        - Example:
            Server 1
                ↓
            Server 1 + Server 2 + Server 3

2. Scalability Principles

    > Decentralization
        - Avoid single point of failure
        - Distribute workload across multiple services/servers
        - Opposite of tightly coupled monolith

    > Independence
        - Components should work independently
        - Failure in one component should not affect others

    > Modularity
        - Divide system into smaller modules/services
        - Easier development, testing, maintenance, and scaling

3. Web Layer Replication
    - Multiple copies of web servers
    - Handles incoming HTTP requests
    - Load balancer distributes traffic
    - Improves availability and scalability

    Example:
        Load Balancer
             ↓
        Web1 Web2 Web3


4. Service Layer Replication
    - Multiple copies of same service/business logic
    - Handles application processing
    - Improves throughput and fault tolerance

    Example:
        User Service 1
        User Service 2
        User Service 3        

5. DB Replication
    - Creating copies of the same database on multiple servers
    - Primary DB handles writes
    - Replica DBs receive copied data
    - Used for high availability, backup, and read scaling

    Example:

        Primary DB
            ↓
      Replica 1
      Replica 2

